  "local_port": 51816,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the best free online course for website design?",
  "response": "If you're looking for the best free online courses for website design, here are some highly recommended options that cater to different skill levels:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Responsive Web Design Certification (freeCodeCamp)**\n   - **Platform**: freeCodeCamp\n   - **Description**: This comprehensive course covers HTML, CSS, and responsive design principles. You'll learn by building real-world projects and earn a certification upon completion.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - Basic HTML and CSS\n     - Responsive design using CSS Flexbox and Grid\n     - Accessibility best practices\n   - **Link**: [freeCodeCamp Responsive Web Design](https://www.freecodecamp.org/learn/)\n\n---\n\n### **2. Web Design for Everybody (University of Michigan)**\n   - **Platform**: Coursera (free to audit)\n   - **Description**: This beginner-friendly course series offers a thorough introduction to web design, focusing on HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. You can audit the course for free.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - HTML5 and CSS3 basics\n     - Responsive design\n     - Introduction to JavaScript\n   - **Link**: [Web Design for Everybody](https://www.coursera.org/specializations/web-design)\n\n---\n\n### **3. Introduction to HTML and CSS (Khan Academy)**\n   - **Platform**: Khan Academy\n   - **Description**: A beginner-friendly course that teaches the fundamentals of HTML and CSS through interactive exercises.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - Basic HTML tags and structure\n     - Styling with CSS\n     - Simple web page design\n   - **Link**: [Khan Academy HTML/CSS](https://www.khanacademy.org/computing)\n\n---\n\n### **4. HTML & CSS Crash Course (The Net Ninja)**\n   - **Platform**: YouTube\n   - **Description**: A video-based crash course that covers the essentials of HTML and CSS in a clear and engaging manner.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - HTML and CSS basics\n     - How to structure and style a webpage\n   - **Link**: [The Net Ninja HTML & CSS Crash Course](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4cUxeGkcC9ivBf_eKCPIAYXWzLlPAm6G)\n\n---\n\n### **5. Learn Web Development (MDN Web Docs)**\n   - **Platform**: Mozilla Developer Network (MDN)\n   - **Description**: A self-paced, comprehensive guide to web development, including HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - Core web development concepts\n     - Responsive design and accessibility\n     - Advanced CSS techniques\n   - **Link**: [MDN Web Docs Learning Area](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn)\n\n---\n\n### **6. Frontend Web Development Bootcamp (Scrimba)**\n   - **Platform**: Scrimba\n   - **Description**: An interactive course that teaches HTML, CSS, and JavaScript through hands-on coding challenges.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - Building responsive websites\n     - JavaScript for interactivity\n     - Modern web design practices\n   - **Link**: [Scrimba Frontend Bootcamp](https://scrimba.com/learn/frontend)\n\n---\n\n### **7. Web Design Basics (Google Web Fundamentals)**\n   - **Platform**: Google Developers\n   - **Description**: A resource-rich guide to modern web design, focusing on responsive design, performance, and accessibility.\n   - **What you\u2019ll learn**:\n     - Responsive design principles\n     - Web performance optimization\n     - Best practices for accessibility\n   - **Link**: [Google Web Fundamentals](https://web.dev/learn/)\n\n---\n\n### **Tips for Choosing the Right Course**\n- **Beginners**: Start with freeCodeCamp, Khan Academy, or The Net Ninja.\n- **Intermediate Learners**: Try MDN Web Docs or Scrimba.\n- **Certification Seekers**: Go for freeCodeCamp or Coursera (free to audit).\n\nAll of these courses are excellent resources to get started with website design for free!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
